article.description:
Vince Carter had 18 points and 11 rebounds, and
Antonio Davis scored 19 to lead five Raptors in double figures in
Toronto's 104-92 victory over the Boston Celtics on Sunday.
article.headline: Walker scores 38 points before being ejected
article.linkText: Walker's 38 not enough to lift Celtics over Raptors
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- This time, the Toronto Raptors took advantage of Paul Pierce's absence.
Carter

Vince Carter had 18 points and 11 rebounds, and Antonio Davis scored 19 to lead five Raptors in double figures in Toronto's 104-92 victory over the Boston Celtics on Sunday. Boston's Antoine Walker had a season-high 38 points but was ejected after receiving two technical fouls in the last two minutes. The Celtics were without Pierce for the second straight game. Pierce, the NBA's fourth-leading scorer, strained his lower back when he slipped on ice about a week ago. The Celtics beat the visiting Raptors on Friday night without Pierce. "It's very difficult to play without our leading scorer, somebody that commands a lot of attention,'' Walker said. "We are trying to weather the storm right now. We're 1-1 without him. Hopefully, we'll get a win tomorrow in Memphis before we get back home.'' Pierce said he was feeling better before the game, but he didn't know if he would play Monday. Boston coach Jim O'Brien said he had a hunch that Pierce would play. O'Brien praised Walker for attacking the basket, but said the other Celtics didn't do enough to help him. "Antoine stepped it up in a big way,'' O'Brien said. "He did a very, very, good job inside and that's what you expect of Antoine.'' Davis had 14 points as Toronto turned a five-point halftime deficit into a 14-point lead by the end of the third quarter. Toronto scored a season-high 38 points in the third. Carter's dunk capped a 10-0 run as Toronto took a 65-55 lead midway through the third. Walker's layup and hook shot cut the lead to one, but the Raptors followed with a 9-0 run. Voshon Lenard's 3-pointer gave Toronto a 10-point lead with 3:06 left in the quarter, and his 3-pointer just before the end of the quarter made it a 14-point lead. Rafer Alston's 3-pointer gave Toronto a 16-point lead in the fourth, but Walker had six points as the Celtics followed with a 14-2 run. Walker's layup cut Toronto's lead to four with 4{ minutes left, but Alvin Williams followed with a jumper, a steal and a layup to make it an eight-point game with less then three minutes to go. Walker then grabbed an offensive rebound but was called for a foul. He slammed the ball to the floor, earning his first technical with 1:46 left. After Carter followed with a free throw, O'Brien received a technical for arguing with the officials. Carter followed with another free throw, and later made a jumper, giving Toronto a 102-88 lead with 1:30 left. Walker then was ejected as Carter made two more free throws with a minute remaining. "I wasn't frustrated. It was just in the heat of the battle, you want to win,'' Walker said. "We let the game slip away from us.'' Jerome Williams added 18 points, and Alvin Williams and Lenard each had 15 for the Raptors, who are 8-5 since Carter returned to the lineup after missing 23 consecutive games with a strained right knee. "We're not having the best season, but we've been able to turn it around and to show people this what could have been if we were healthy,'' Carter said. Walker had 17 points, most of them inside, as Boston outscored Toronto 28-12 in the paint and led 49-44 at halftime. Game notes
The Raptors outrebounded Boston 47-32. ... Walker went 17-for-31 from the field. ... Boston outscored Toronto 52-32 in the paint. ... Carter left the game in the second quarter with a twisted right ankle, but later returned. He finished 6-for-14 from the field.
